land":"Yorkshire, England","Spaldington, Yorkshire, England":"Spaldington, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Butler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a word that originally denoted a wine steward, usually the chief servant of a medieval household, from Norman French <i>butuiller</i> (Old French <i>bouteillier</i>, Latin <i>buticularius</i>, from <i>buticula</i> ‘bottle’). In the large households of royalty and the most powerful nobility, the title came to denote an officer of high rank and responsibility, only nominally concerned with the supply of wine, if at all. As well as being widespread in England, this is also the surname of an important Irish family, descended from Theobald FitzWalter, who was appointed Chief Butler of Ireland by King Henry II in 1177. It is Gaelicized as <i>de Buitléir</i>.","English: occasionally perhaps an occupational name from Middle English <i>boteler</i> ‘maker of bottles (usually of leather)’, a derivative of Middle English <i>botel</i>, Old French <i>bo(u)teille</i> ‘bottle’ and synonymous with <i>Botelmaker</i>.","Americanized form of French   Bouthillier   (see   Bouteiller  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Buttler","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Butler  .","German: occupational name for a village tavern owner, from French <i>bouteillier</i> ‘butler’.","Americanized form of German <b>Buttlar</b>: habitational name from a place so named in Thuringia."]},{"name":"Bouthillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Jacques, Normand, Philippe, Yves.","French: variant of   Bouteiller  . This name is sometimes Americanized as   Butler  . Compare   Boutilier  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert le Butler was born about 1250, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Richard le Botiler, was 19 and his mother, Mrs. Richard le Botiler, was 17. He had at least 1 son with Constance del Hay."},"et":{"about 1250–":"umbes 1250–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1233–Male":"1233–Surnud","1235–Female":"1235–Surnud","about 1250":"umbes 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1235":"1235","1233":"1233","1265":"1265","1250":"1250","about 1265":"umbes 1265","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Spaldington, Yorkshire, England":"Spaldington, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1250–":"noin 1250–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1265–Male":"1265–Kuollut","1233–Male":"1233–Kuollut","1235–Female":"1235–Kuollut","about 1250":"noin 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1235":"1235","1233":"1233","1265":"1265","1250":"1250","about 1265":"noin 1265","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Spaldington, Yorkshire, England":"Spaldington, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1250–":"environ 1250–Décédé","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1250–Female":"1250–Décédée","1265–Male":"1265–Décédé","1233–Male":"1233–Décédé","1235–Female":"1235–Décédée","about 1250":"environ 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1235":"1235","1233":"1233","1265":"1265","1250":"1250","about 1265":"environ 1265","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Everwyck, Angleterre","Spaldington, Yorkshire, England":"Spaldington, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Robert le Butler est né environ 1250, à Everwyck, Angleterre, son père, Richard le Botiler, avait 19 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Richard le Botiler, avait 17 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Constance del Hay."},"de":{"about 1250–":"um 1250–Verstorben","1250–Male":"1250–Verstorben","1250–Female":"1250–Verstorben","1265–Male":"1265–Verstorben","1233–Male":"1233–Verstorben","1235–Female":"1235–Verstorben","about 1250":"um 1250","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1235":"12